caption: A beautiful and delicious place. Will definitely be back.
The corned beef reuben is great, probably the best reuben in the area.

Excellent rugelach. My wife is Jewish and says this place does everything well. I certainly think so. It's nice to have a good place to get a lox bagel without having to travel so far, especially with covid.

I ordered 3 sandwiches, a lean pastrami on a knish, a pastrami on rye bread and a corned beef on rye. Let's start with the lean pastrami on a knish I think they didn't want to tell me they didn't have any lean pastrami...and that knish was so greasy when I bit into it it literally squirted   all over my apt I hope I can get my deposit back, next the pastrami on rye was dark I never seen pastrami that color and It was overcooked and burnt and greasy. I put the corned beef in the fridge I needed a break I will try it tomorrow and I think the pickle was a hybrid because I never tasted one like that....p.s. the pic makes the pastrami look better than real life.
Delicious traditional Jewish deli food
Good location and great customer service here I always get my sandwiches here and coffee.

We had a small pod gathering (shiva) for my partner's dad who passed away and for her birthday celebration. We had the smoked goodness platter for 8 people delivered along with bagels and bialys. Everyone could not stop raving about the quality of the fish which included sable, lox and a luscious whole whitefish. One friend commented that the quality of the fish surpassed  even the most renowned establishments. From now on we will only order a smoked goodness platter from Shelsky's on Court Street. Thank you so much for making our gathering so delicious.
The most amazing lox sandwiches around! The Gatsby is a must have!! Every sandwich is carefully prepared and so fresh
Ordered an everything bagel with veggie shmear. Bagel was way too chewy and dense - almost under proofed and lacked a good crust. Also - physically very small bagels. Can’t recommend.

Absolutely love this place! The tribute bagel sandwich is life!!! So so good! If you are a smoked fish lover it is an absolute must try. Also love that they have halva.

Some of the best bagels and lox you will find anywhere in NYC.  Delicious prepared foods, phenomenal matzo ball and other soups.  Caviar at new years.  Bris boys of Brooklyn -- this place is the best!

I placed a large takeout order today for a Bris - The food was incredible and the package Shelsky's put together was turnkey, with environmentally friendly dishes spoons and forks.  The blood orange juice was a big hit. The coffee was great but the platters and salmon and whitefish salads were top shelf, plus the dessert tray and fruit tray.  Worth every penny!!!  They delivered what they promised.

Admittedly not a fan of fish so I just got a bagel with some cream cheese. It was very good if a little pricey. The people I was with who got the more popular fish sandwiches seemed to think the same thing.

Just asked for a plain bagel (at 5:00, not fresh at this point) with whitefish. $13... A bit absurd. Nothing mind blowing about this bagel at all. Not going back anytime soon. Go to the place down the street if you’re not a chump (like me).
Solid bagels, smoked fish, and pickled herring
This place is the best.
Great smoked salmon expertly cut. Worth a visit.

Dissatisfied with the service. I was given half a bagel and was told that they’re hand rolled and they couldn’t control the way the bagel was shaped. They agreed to bring another, which was almost as bad as the first. Then when I asked for a pound of tuna and it was over the amount I asked for, the person serving me was very reluctant to remove any. It took him three times to remove the excess and I had to ask each time to remove more (it was still over, but I finally gave up and took it). The food here is good, the bagels are ok, but my experience with their service was terrible. They seem to take their customers for granted. Hence, the two star review.
Comparable to Russ and Daughters if not in some ways better.
Expensive, and overrated. The food is not what they are hyped up to be, plus they charge you an arm and a leg.

Great choice of quality food: bagel’s & lox, whitefish salad and all the trimmings! Even the chicken soup works well on a hot winter day. Worth the visit!

Phenomenal. I think the Great Gatsby could make it onto my shortlist for a final meal. Can’t go wrong with any of their option though. And the service is great too.

If you like a chewy - I mean CHEWY bagel, this is your place. The first bagel I had was “stick to the roof of your mouth” chewy. Didn’t seem right. Almost as if the bagel wasn’t allowed to rest after baking. That bagel had salmon cream cheese, which was only ok. The salmon flavor didn’t really come through. Second experience, bagel was still chewy, but not as much. Crunchy exterior and lots of seeds, which I appreciate. This bagel had the white fish salad, that was a hit. Not too salty like others usually are. Trying the pastrami next. Coffee is just average.

I wish I had known this deli earlier. The pastrami is up there with the best that the city has to offer, and the sweets are also ridiculously good. Even the bread is memorable. Pepe gave me the warmest attention I've had at a deli; unexpected and very welcome. It's not cheap, but it's so filling and comforting that it's worth every penny. I can't wait to try other options from the menu.

Shelsky's provides first-rate appetizing and deli.  Excellent smoked fish, as well as pastrami and other cured meats.  I am also fond of their homemade salads, particularly the egg salad with cornichons.  As a New Yorker with high standards for smoked fish slicing, I can tell you that you can often get near-transparent slices from Shelsky's.  Peter runs a good shop.

Smoked white fish? Yes Please!  You'd think getting that perfect toasted bagel with a perfect spread would be easy to find in NYC, but it really isn't. Until you hit Shelsky's. Then your world has finally been complete.  I love the old school deli vibe Shelsky's offers when you walk in and absolutely love that they carry British products on their shelves. Items such as golden syrup, marmite, jaffa cakes and more.  They serve up some fantastic fish sandwiches and also meat (cold cut) sandwiches. I ordered a toasted bagel with smoked white fish, lox & veggies. Trust me it was everything I dreamed of and more. I rate the bagel almost as good as my bagels from Frankels but the store definitely gets a 10.  I do think the bagel was slightly overpriced for what they're offering hence the fallen star but I'd definitely go back for a bagel if I was in the neighborhood. I also very much recommend them for large platters. Their fish seem super fresh and of high grade.
Top quality fish, charming location, lovely and friendly staff.
Incredible food, incredible staff, cool owner, it’s a gem.
The owners Pete and Louis are very cool.

What can you say about Shelsky's? It's the best! Any hankering you have of smoked fish or bagels or any Jewish specialty foods, just stop by! It's old school, grab-a-number and high quality. Watch out for the crowds weekend mornings.
Went there on a food tour. Eclectic neat place. Worth going out of your way to visit. You won't be disappointed

This deli knows it’s Jewish food! Everything about its offerings - from the bialy to the babka - is authentic and delicious. The smell welcomes you into a grocery of decades past, and it is a great spot to source the food you’ve craved for a while but never found. It’s close to being known as the Russ and Daughters of north Brooklyn.

Love this place. They will give you a quizzical look if you ask to put their Salmon Jerky on a bagel. I guess you're supposed to eat it by itself? But I love it. Scallion Cream Cheese + Salmon Beef Jerky + Red Onions on an Everything Bagel is my favorite. Everything else there is fantastic too.
So yummy. Classic Brooklyn spot. Go smoked fish.

The "Great Gatsby" sandwich was unbelievably good.  Pastrami-cured salmon with honey-mustard.  Not a combination I would have dreamt up myself, but nonetheless the best thing I've tasted in recent memory. I could have easily eaten two of them.  I've been here for lunch twice.  The previous time I got the "Fancy Pants", which was merely ok and not particularly noteworthy. So first lunch experience garners 3 starts, and the second garners 5.  Which would average 4, but the "Great Gatsby" was so exceptional it needs to be 5 overall.

Two words: salmon jerky. Is it expensive? Yes. Is it one of the best things you'll ever put in your mouth? Also yes.  On sandwiches: The menu board can be hella overwhelming, especially your first time in, so I'd recommend checking it out online first. Some sandwiches are a bit forgettable (and could comparably be found elsewhere for a lower price) but my go-to here, the Great Gatsby, is, well, pretty effing great.

Three bad salmon experiences in a row over a period of several months, and that's the end of that: I'd rather take the F train to Russ & Daughters. Shelsky's nova sits too long and its edges go hard and plasticky. The staff doesn't know what we're talking about because they don't know fish. This morning, getting food for a brunch, they didn't have bagels or rugalach--neither had come in yet, an hour after they opened. The rugalach are heavenly (when you can get them) and their other foods are good. The bagels are so-so. But you can't count on their having things and you can't count on their fish. And don't try to place an order and have them deliver it: they messed up 100% of the time through the years we've been trying to buy from them. It's really too bad. I want to like them.
I love this place so much. Amazing smoked fish, pickled herring, and delicious Mill Basin bagels.

Awful service...slow...slow...slow. Prepare to wait for the one of five servers to walk around while you wait and wait.
Classic appetizing done perfectly! Nova is high quality and cut thin. Their sandwiches are amazing too.
Go.

Sometimes you just need to do one thing and do it well. Shelsky's does smoked fish and they do it exceptionally well. I had some of the best lox of my life from this shop: sliced paper thin, melts in your mouth, unbelievable. Their onion rolls are also fresh and delicious. And they get bonus points for carrying tofu cream cheese for those of us who are lactose intolerant. The fish isn't cheap, but it is exquisite.
Why go anywhere else?  The assortment of fish is incredible, plus their sandwiches are a fun mix of classics and scrumptuous new creations with unique combinations of ingredients.

I work at Escape Guesthouse in Boerum Hill, Brooklyn and often get special requests for Shelsky's from guests that end up at our Brooklyn Bed and Breakfast from all corners of the globe. They are incredibly accommodating and really make my day awesome when I order from them. What I like most about Shelky's is that even though they usually open at 8AM, I have been able to develop a great working relationship with their staff, and they know that I try to have breakfast for my guests ready at 8AM. That means I can call them around 7:45 when someone is there setting up for the day, tell them how many guests I am currently hosting, and what they like to eat, and someone at Shelky's well get everything organized for me and I can run in and run out to serve my guests on time. They make getting amazing smoked salmon super convenient-- totally worth the expense. On top of it all, the staff is super friendly and knowledgable about their product. Bagels are tasty and our guests love it all. Thanks for being such a great neighborhood establishment-- you help make our Brooklyn B&B great!

A lovely tiled temple to the Jewish appetizing tradition, with a top-notch selection of locally smoked fish, pickles. bagels, bialys and cream cheese served, incongruously but charmingly, by an Irish-accented Robert Pattinson lookalike. Very very possibly the best smoked fish in the city, and it kind of hurts me to say this because I love my old-timey stalwarts like Russ and Daughters, but the tastebuds know what they know. The Nova is meltingly tender, subtle and so fresh it retains some of the delicate flavor of sashimi, and the Mexican Achiote-seasoned version was a interesting variation. They also smoke some unusual local species, such as bluefish. I brought home a pound of delicious house-made rugulach too. Worth a trip from any borough, but for Carroll Gardens residents there's no reason to go any place else for Sunday brunch treats.
Food is good, but you're paying for it. Much of the value here is the location.
